    contextPoints: [
      'Priestley wrote the play in 1945 but set it in 1912, exploiting the dramatic irony of the audience\'s knowledge of two World Wars, the sinking of the Titanic, and the collapse of the British Empire to discredit Birling\'s confident capitalist predictions.',
      'The play was first performed in the Soviet Union (Moscow, 1945) before opening in London in 1946, reflecting Priestley\'s international socialist sympathies and the global appetite for left-wing art after World War Two.',
      'Priestley was a committed socialist who helped found the Common Wealth Party and whose BBC "Postscripts" broadcasts during World War Two promoted social equality, reaching an audience of millions and angering the Conservative establishment.',
      'The 1945 Labour landslide election — which introduced the NHS and the welfare state — provides the essential political context for the play. Priestley wrote it to support the case for collective social responsibility and government intervention.',
      'Edwardian England (1901-1910, extended culturally to 1914) was characterised by extreme class division, limited workers\' rights, no welfare state, and restricted women\'s suffrage. The 1912 setting allows Priestley to dramatise the specific social conditions he believed caused the catastrophes of the twentieth century.',
      'The well-made play tradition, with its unities of time, place, and action, influences the structure of An Inspector Calls. The single evening, single setting, and linear revelation create an intense claustrophobic atmosphere that mirrors the characters\' moral entrapment.',
      'The suffragette movement was at its peak in 1912. Women had limited legal rights, could not vote, and were economically dependent on men. This context is essential for understanding Eva Smith\'s vulnerability and the gender dynamics of the play.',
      'The General Strike of 1926 and the labour unrest of the early twentieth century provide relevant context for the workers\' strike that leads to Eva\'s dismissal. Priestley was deeply sympathetic to the labour movement and uses Birling\'s hostility to strikers to critique the capitalist suppression of workers\' rights.',
      'Priestley served in World War One and was deeply affected by the experience. His belief that the war was caused by the same ruling-class selfishness dramatised in the play informs the Inspector\'s apocalyptic warning about "fire and blood and anguish." The play channels Priestley\'s conviction that social reform was the only way to prevent future catastrophes.'
    ],

    examTips: [
      'WJEC Eduqas Paper 2, Section A requires you to write about a modern drama text. You will receive an extract and a question. You MUST refer to the extract AND the wider play — responses that only discuss the extract will not achieve the higher bands.',
      'The WJEC mark scheme rewards AO1 (response to text, use of quotations), AO2 (analysis of language, form, and structure), AO3 (context), and AO4 (use of a range of vocabulary and sentence structures for clarity and effect). Ensure your response addresses all four.',
      'Always embed quotations within your sentences rather than presenting them as standalone blocks. Short, precise quotations analysed in detail score more highly than long quotations with superficial commentary.',
      'For AO2, analyse Priestley\'s methods: dramatic irony, the well-made play structure, the Inspector as a dramatic device, stage directions, and the cyclical ending. Do not simply describe what happens — explain HOW Priestley constructs meaning.',
      'For AO3, link context to the text rather than bolting it on. Instead of writing a separate paragraph about context, weave contextual knowledge into your analysis: "Priestley uses Birling\'s speech to critique the Edwardian capitalist class who..." is better than "In 1912, there was a lot of inequality."',
      'Plan your response before writing. A structured argument (introduction, 3-4 analytical paragraphs, conclusion) will always outperform an unstructured response, even if the latter contains strong individual points.',
      'Use Priestley\'s name frequently — "Priestley presents," "Priestley suggests," "Priestley uses" — to demonstrate that you understand the text as a constructed artefact with authorial intent, not as a real event.',
      'For the highest bands (Grade 8-9), develop a critical perspective. Consider alternative interpretations: is Gerald genuinely compassionate or subtly exploitative? Is the Inspector a socialist hero or an authoritarian figure? Exploring ambiguity demonstrates sophisticated reading.',
      'The cyclical ending — the telephone announcing a real inspector\'s visit — is one of the most commonly examined structural features. Be prepared to analyse its dramatic effect (shock, unresolved tension) and its thematic significance (those who fail to learn are condemned to repeat their mistakes).',
      'When discussing the Inspector, avoid simply describing him as "mysterious." Instead, analyse his function: he is a dramatic device that enables Priestley to structure the play as a sequence of confessions, building cumulative guilt and driving the moral argument towards its conclusion.'
    ],

