    structuralFeatures: [
      {
        feature: 'The Well-Made Play Structure',
        analysis:
          'An Inspector Calls follows the conventions of the well-made play: it observes the three unities (one time, one place, one action), builds through a series of revelations, and reaches a climactic crisis. Priestley uses this tight structure to create claustrophobic intensity — the Birlings cannot escape the Inspector\'s interrogation, just as they cannot escape their moral culpability. The single setting (the dining room) becomes a courtroom in which each character is tried and judged.'
      },
      {
        feature: 'The Cyclical Ending',
        analysis:
          'The telephone rings announcing a real police inspector is on his way to investigate a girl\'s suicide. This cyclical ending serves multiple functions: it punishes the characters who refused to learn (the older Birlings and Gerald must face the ordeal again), it rewards those who did learn (Sheila and Eric\'s moral growth is validated), and it sends a message to the audience that the consequences of social irresponsibility are inescapable. The ending also creates a powerful sense of theatrical shock that ensures the play\'s message lingers long after the curtain falls.'
      },
      {
        feature: 'Dramatic Irony',
        analysis:
          'Priestley exploits the gap between the 1912 setting and the 1945 audience to create sustained dramatic irony. Birling\'s predictions about the Titanic, war, and social stability are all proven catastrophically wrong by history. This irony operates throughout the play, undermining Birling\'s authority and, by extension, the capitalist ideology he represents. The audience\'s superior knowledge makes Birling a figure of ridicule and ensures that his worldview is rejected before the Inspector even arrives.'
      },
      {
        feature: 'Sequential Confessions',
        analysis:
          'The Inspector interrogates each character in turn, creating a structure of escalating revelations. Each confession is more damning than the last: Birling\'s dismissal leads to Sheila\'s jealousy, then Gerald\'s affair, then Mrs Birling\'s rejection, and finally Eric\'s assault. This cumulative structure builds dramatic tension and also constructs a chain of causation that implicates the entire family — and, by extension, the entire class system — in Eva\'s death.'
      },
      {
        feature: 'Stage Directions and Lighting',
        analysis:
          'Priestley\'s stage directions are thematically significant. At the start, the lighting is described as "pink and intimate" — suggesting the rosy, comfortable self-deception of the Birling family. When the Inspector arrives, it becomes "brighter and harder," symbolising the harsh light of moral scrutiny. This shift from comfortable illusion to uncomfortable truth mirrors the play\'s movement from complacency to accountability. WJEC examiners reward analysis of stage directions as evidence of Priestley\'s control over the audience\'s experience and his deliberate manipulation of mood and symbolism.'
      }
    ],

