    contextPoints: [
      'Willy Russell grew up in working-class Liverpool and left school at fifteen with no qualifications, later returning to education as a mature student. His personal experience of class barriers directly informs the play\'s argument about the damage caused by educational and economic inequality.',
      'Blood Brothers was first performed in 1983, during Margaret Thatcher\'s government, a period of mass unemployment, deindustrialisation, and widening inequality in Britain. The closure of the factory where Mickey works reflects the destruction of working-class communities across the North of England during this period.',
      'Liverpool in the 1960s-1980s experienced severe economic decline, high unemployment, and social deprivation. The city also had a strong tradition of community solidarity and cultural creativity (the Beatles, the Liverpool Poets), and Russell draws on both the hardship and the vitality of working-class Liverpool culture.',
      'The welfare state, established after World War Two, was intended to provide a safety net for the most vulnerable. Russell\'s play dramatises the failure of these systems — Mrs Johnstone receives inadequate support, and the rehousing in Skelmersdale does not solve the structural problems of poverty.',
      'The play draws on the classical dramatic tradition of separated twins (Shakespeare\'s Comedy of Errors, Twelfth Night) and the genre of the changeling narrative. However, Russell transforms these comic conventions into tragedy, using the familiar form to deliver a political message about class.',
      'The Brechtian influence is evident in the use of the Narrator, direct address, songs, and the revelation of the ending at the start. These epic theatre techniques prevent emotional immersion and encourage the audience to analyse the social forces at work rather than simply feeling sympathy for the characters.',
      'The 11-plus examination system, which sorted children into grammar schools and secondary moderns at age eleven, is relevant to understanding how education reinforced class division. Edward\'s private schooling and Mickey\'s comprehensive education reflect a two-tier system that perpetuated inequality rather than enabling social mobility.',
      'Russell\'s other works, including Educating Rita and Our Day Out, share Blood Brothers\' concern with how the class system limits working-class potential. This broader body of work demonstrates that Blood Brothers is not an isolated statement but part of Russell\'s lifelong engagement with educational and social inequality.'
    ],

    examTips: [
      'WJEC Eduqas Paper 2 requires you to write about a modern drama text. You will be given an extract and a question. You MUST write about the extract AND the wider play — ignoring either element will limit your mark.',
      'Blood Brothers is a musical, and Russell\'s use of songs is a crucial dramatic method. Always analyse the songs as a technique — they reveal characters\' inner emotions, create irony, advance the plot, and contribute to the Brechtian style. Ignoring the music is a common weakness in exam responses.',
      'The Narrator is a key dramatic device. Discuss his role as chorus, conscience, and fate figure. Analyse how his songs and interjections create dramatic irony and encourage the audience to think critically about the causes of the tragedy.',
      'For AO2, focus on Russell\'s methods: dramatic irony (the audience knows the twins\' fate from the start), parallel structure (showing the twins at the same age in different circumstances), music, staging, and the Narrator as a Brechtian device.',
      'For AO3, integrate context into your analysis rather than adding it as a separate paragraph. Reference Thatcher\'s Britain, deindustrialisation, educational inequality, and the welfare state, but always link these to specific moments in the text.',
      'Compare the twins systematically. The parallel structure of the play is its most important method — every scene implicitly asks the audience to compare Mickey and Edward\'s experiences and draw conclusions about the role of class.',
      'Always use Russell\'s name to show you understand the text is a construct: "Russell presents," "Russell structures," "Russell uses the Narrator to suggest." This demonstrates AO2 awareness of authorial intent and dramatic craft.',
      'For the highest marks, consider the play\'s ambiguity: does Russell present the tragedy as caused by superstition, class, individual choices, or some combination? Exploring this question demonstrates the evaluative thinking required at Grades 8-9.',
      'Pay attention to how Russell uses dialect and register to mark class difference. Mickey\'s colloquial Liverpool dialect contrasts with Edward\'s standard English. Analysing these linguistic choices demonstrates AO2 awareness of how language constructs character and meaning.',
      'The staging of Blood Brothers is significant. Russell specifies a bare stage with minimal props, which focuses attention on the characters and their words rather than on realistic settings. This sparse staging is a Brechtian technique that supports the play\'s status as a political parable rather than a naturalistic drama.',
      'When writing about Mrs Johnstone and Mrs Lyons, avoid simplistic judgements ("Mrs Lyons is evil"). Russell presents both women as products of their circumstances. The best responses explore how the class system forces both mothers into impossible positions — one too poor to keep her child, the other too privileged to develop genuine maternal instincts.',
      'Remember that Blood Brothers spans approximately twenty-five years. Track how characters change over time: Mickey\'s energy becomes depression, Edward\'s innocence becomes privilege, Linda\'s confidence becomes desperation. Discussing character arcs demonstrates understanding of the play\'s structure and Russell\'s methods.'
    ],

